<Layout title="Alternatives">
  <article class="prose-measure mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-4">Screen-light pedagogies (a brief overview)</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-600 italic">A short, neutral primer on recognized educational approaches that de-emphasize early-grade screen use. The point is reassurance — these are established pedagogies, not fringe experiments — not advocacy for any specific approach.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">Waldorf / Steiner</h2>
    <p>Waldorf schools follow a Steiner-influenced developmental approach that intentionally limits screens in early grades, emphasizing handwork, imaginative play, and direct experience. Reading instruction typically begins later than in mainstream curricula. The umbrella organization in North America is the
      <a href="https://www.waldorfeducation.org/">Association of Waldorf Schools of North America (AWSNA)</a>.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">Montessori</h2>
    <p>Montessori classrooms use specific manipulative materials, multi-age groupings, and self-directed work cycles. Most Montessori programs minimize early screen use as a matter of method rather than ideology. The two largest umbrella associations in the US are the
      <a href="https://amshq.org/">American Montessori Society (AMS)</a> and
      <a href="https://amiusa.org/">Association Montessori Internationale - USA (AMI/USA)</a>.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">Forest schools / nature-based pre-K and K</h2>
    <p>Forest schools, primarily a Scandinavian and UK tradition, conduct most instruction outdoors. In the US they typically appear at the pre-K and kindergarten level. The
      <a href="https://naturalstart.org/">Natural Start Alliance</a> maintains a directory of nature-based early-childhood programs in North America.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">Classical education</h2>
    <p>Classical schools follow a trivium-based sequence (grammar, logic, rhetoric) and emphasize Latin, primary texts, and structured memorization in early grades. Some classical programs are religious, others secular. Screen use in early grades varies but tends to be limited.
      <a href="https://societyforclassicallearning.org/">The Society for Classical Learning</a> is one umbrella body.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">Homeschool co-ops and microschools</h2>
    <p>Homeschooling is legal in NY under
      <a href="https://www.nysed.gov/family-community-engagement/home-instruction-new-york-state">NYSED's home instruction regulations</a> and requires filing an Individualized Home Instruction Plan (IHIP). Co-ops and microschools (small in-person groups, often part-time) have grown rapidly post-2020. The
      <a href="https://www.hslda.org/">Home School Legal Defense Association</a> is one resource; for NY-specific guidance, NYSED's site is the primary source.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">A note on framing</h2>
    <p>Most parents reading this page will not pull their child from a public-school 1:1 program; the more common path is to remain in district and exercise the rights that §2-d and FERPA provide. This page is here so that parents who want to understand the broader landscape — what other approaches exist, who runs them, where to read more — can do so without sifting through marketing material.</p>
  </article>
